In .NET 10 (starting with preview builds), `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize` was deprecated on Android because the underlying `adjustResize` mode was removed in newer Android APIs. The replacement is **edge-to-edge** display combined with **keyboard inset handling**.

Here's the fix:

**1. In your `MauiProgram.cs`, enable edge-to-edge and use `AdjustPan` or handle insets:**

```csharp
#if ANDROID
builder.ConfigureMauiHandlers(handlers =>
{
    Microsoft.Maui.Handlers.WindowHandler.Mapper.AppendToMapping("KeyboardInsets", (handler, view) =>
    {
        var activity = handler.PlatformView as Android.App.Activity;
        if (activity?.Window != null)
        {
            AndroidX.Core.View.WindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(activity.Window, false);
        }
    });
});
#endif
```

**2. Wrap your chat layout in a `Grid` that responds to keyboard insets using the new `SafeAreaPadding` or handle it manually:**

```xml
<Grid>
    <Grid.RowDefinitions>
        <RowDefinition Height="*" />
        <RowDefinition Height="Auto" />
    </Grid.RowDefinitions>

    <CollectionView Grid.Row="0" ItemsSource="{Binding Messages}" />

    <Entry Grid.Row="1" Placeholder="Type a message..."
           Margin="{OnPlatform Android='0,0,0,0'}" />
</Grid>
```

**3. The simplest working approach for .NET 10 Android — listen to insets in your `MainActivity.cs`:**

```csharp
using AndroidX.Core.View;
using AndroidX.Core.Graphics;

protected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)
{
    base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);

    WindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(Window!, false);

    ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener(Window!.DecorView, new InsetsListener());
}

private class InsetsListener : Java.Lang.Object, IOnApplyWindowInsetsListener
{
    public WindowInsetsCompat OnApplyWindowInsets(Android.Views.View v, WindowInsetsCompat insets)
    {
        var imeInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime());
        var navInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.NavigationBars());

        int bottomPadding = Math.Max(imeInsets.Bottom, navInsets.Bottom);
        v.SetPadding(0, 0, 0, bottomPadding);

        return insets;
    }
}
```

**Key takeaway:** Replace `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize` with the `WindowInsetsCompat` API — listen for `Ime()` insets and apply bottom padding to your root view. This is the Android-recommended approach going forward and what .NET 10 expects you to use.
